Refactors the `Class` API so that a [standardized ECMAScript](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Classes) class is used. This also allows classes to be sub-classed by using the new ECMAScript syntax:

```js
class Parent extends L.Class {
  initialize() {
    console.log("Parent initialize called.");
  }
}

class Child extends Parent {
  initialize() {
    super.initialize();
    console.log("Child initialize called.");
  }
}

Parent.addInitHook(function () {
  console.log("Parent init hook called.");
});

Child.addInitHook(function () {
  console.log("Child init hook called.");
});

const child = new Child();
```

As shown above `addInitHook()` continues to work as expected. There are however some things that do not work as one might be used to with the `Class.extend()` method.

## Statics

*Before*:
```js
const MyClass = L.Class.extend({
  statics: {
    FOO: "bar",
  },
});

MyClass.FOO; // 'bar'
```

*After:*
```js
class MyClass extends L.Class {
  static FOO = "";
}

MyClass.FOO; // 'bar'
```

## Includes (or mixins)

*Before:*
```js
const MyMixin = {
    foo: function () {},
    bar: 5
};

const MyClass = L.Class.extend({
    includes: MyMixin
});

const a = new MyClass();
a.foo();
```

*After:*
Passing in `includes` is no longer possible as this cannot be done when the class is being constructed (proposals welcome). However calling `includes()` statically is still possible:

```js
MyClass.include(MyMixin);
```

